Madness

When Fury is already full, further Fury gain builds overflow. Enough overflow
raises Madness instead of starting another Frenzy. Madness is cumulative: each
level retains the effects of the levels below it. The "bvent" command clears
Fury and Madness outside combat, though high Madness can make Vent fail.

Every Madness level adds 5% base weapon resistance before Thick Hide,
Defiance mastery, and scar effects. Madness also removes the Fury cost from
Fury-spending abilities, though their other costs and cooldowns still apply.
At any Madness level, combat can briefly disrupt concentration.

  Madness 1: grants 5% base weapon resistance.
  Madness 2: raises base weapon resistance to 10%, adds 15% critical damage,
             and prevents voluntary retreat during combat.
  Madness 3: raises base weapon resistance to 15%, gains a 15% chance to
             counter a weapon hit with the current main-hand or unarmed attack
             without changing targets, and gains a 25% chance to resist
             paralysis or entanglement.
  Madness 4: raises base weapon resistance to 20%, raises the critical damage
             bonus to 30%, can add extra main-hand swings, and has a 35%
             chance per attack to provoke an uncontrolled attack.
  Madness 5: raises base weapon resistance to 25%, raises paralysis and
             entanglement resistance to 50%, gives each hit a 25% chance to
             leave its target Exposed, and leaves the Berserker Exposed.
             Outside combat it also deals 2% maximum health as blunt damage
             every ten seconds. A strong Black Scar reduces this self-damage;
             a fully effective Black Scar suppresses it.

At Madness 4, each main-hand attack has a 15% chance to gain at least one
extra swing, a 4% chance to gain at least two, a 1% chance to gain at least
three, and a 0.25% chance to gain four. One roll determines the whole result,
so most surges are small and the larger bursts are increasingly rare.

At Madness 5 those baseline chances become 20%, 6%, 2%, and 0.5%. Momentum
mastery improves every tier of the distribution. A surge can never add more
than four swings.

Madness is powerful by design, but holding its highest levels carries the risk
of lost control, Exposed, failed Vent attempts, and persistent self-damage.

An uncontrolled attack cannot schedule another uncontrolled attack while it
is pending or executing. Frenzy pulse attack rounds also cannot generate
uncontrolled attacks. Normal combat rounds may still trigger one at Madness 4
or 5, but the resulting bonus round is bounded and non-reentrant.
